Blood Cell Atlas Construction

A comprehensive blood cell atlas is constructed from 10X FLEX single-cell RNA-seq data across a time course (0h, 2h, 4h, 6h, 8h, 24h) with multiple donors. DRVI is used to learn latent representations while regressing out technical batch effects, enabling identification of distinct cell type populations.

Pipeline Overview:

  • Load raw 10X data and extract metadata from cell barcodes
  • Perform quality control and adaptive doublet detection
  • Train DRVI model (16 latents) to capture cell type-level variation
  • Identify and validate cell type clusters using canonical markers
  • Export annotated atlas for downstream analysis

Data Loading and Metadata Extraction

Raw 10X count data is loaded and cell barcodes are parsed to extract metadata. Barcode format follows the pattern: donor_tissue_timepoint.barcode.

In[]:
# Define path to raw 10X data
dataset = '/content/drive/My Drive/neutrophills_singlecell/raw/'
In[]:
# Load raw 10X count matrix
adata = scanpy.read_10x_mtx(dataset)

Quality Control and Doublet Detection

Scrublet is used to compute doublet scores per batch, followed by Gaussian Mixture Model classification to adaptively identify doublets rather than using a fixed threshold.

In[]:
# Parse metadata from cell barcodes (donor, tissue, time, batch) and calculate QC metrics
obs_idx = adata.obs_names.astype(str)

split_df = obs_idx.to_series(index=adata.obs_names).str.extract(r'^(?P<prefix>[^.]+)\.(?P<barcode>.+)$')

meta_df = split_df['prefix'].str.extract(
    r'^(?P<donor>[^_]+)_(?P<tissue>[^_]+)_(?P<time_point>[^_.]+)$'
)

adata.obs['donor'] = meta_df['donor']
adata.obs['tissue'] = meta_df['tissue']
adata.obs['barcode'] = split_df['barcode']
adata.obs['time_point'] = meta_df['time_point']

ordered_time = ['0h', '2h', '4h', '6h', '8h', '24h']
adata.obs['time_point'] = pandas.Categorical(adata.obs['time_point'], categories=ordered_time, ordered=True)


for col in ['donor', 'tissue', 'time_point']:
    adata.obs[col] = adata.obs[col].astype('category')

adata.obs['capture_batch'] = adata.obs['donor'].astype(str) + '_' + adata.obs['time_point'].astype(str)
adata.obs['capture_batch'] = adata.obs['capture_batch'].astype('category')

adata.var['mito'] = adata.var_names.str.startswith('MT-')
scanpy.pp.calculate_qc_metrics(adata, qc_vars=['mito'], inplace=True, log1p=True)


batch_key = 'capture_batch'
In[]:
# Run Scrublet doublet detection per batch
avg_doublet_rate = (adata.obs[batch_key].value_counts() * 8e-6).mean()

scanpy.pp.scrublet(adata, expected_doublet_rate=avg_doublet_rate, batch_key=batch_key)

Cell and Gene Filtering

Genes are filtered to remove mitochondrial, ribosomal, and non-coding transcripts. Cells are filtered based on QC thresholds from the original paper: 200-4000 genes, 200-15000 counts, and <1% mitochondrial content. Predicted doublets are removed.

In[]:
# Use GMM to classify doublets adaptively
scores = adata.obs['doublet_score'].values.reshape(-1, 1) # type: ignore

gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=2, random_state=0)
gmm.fit(scores)

labels = gmm.predict(scores)

cluster_means = {i: scores[labels == i].mean() for i in numpy.unique(labels)}
doublet_cluster = max(cluster_means, key=cluster_means.get) # type: ignore

adata.obs['predicted_doublet'] = labels == doublet_cluster
In[]:
# Filter genes (remove mito/ribo/non-coding) and low-quality cells
mask = ~(adata.var_names.str.startswith('MT-') |
         adata.var_names.str.startswith('RPS') |
         adata.var_names.str.startswith('RPL'))

adata = adata[:, mask].copy() # type: ignore

adata = adata[:, ~adata.var_names.isin(['MALAT1', 'NEAT1'])].copy()

adata = adata[~adata.obs['predicted_doublet']].copy()

adata = adata[
    (adata.obs['n_genes_by_counts'] >= 200) &
    (adata.obs['n_genes_by_counts'] <= 4000) &
    (adata.obs['total_counts'] >= 200) &
    (adata.obs['total_counts'] <= 15000) &
    (adata.obs['pct_counts_mito'] <= 1)
].copy()

Normalization and Feature Selection

Data is normalized to 10,000 counts per cell and log-transformed. 2000 highly variable genes are selected in a batch-aware manner to focus on biologically informative variation.

In[]:
# Save preprocessed data
adata.write_h5ad('/content/drive/My Drive/neutrophills_singlecell/preprocessed_atlas_anndata.h5ad') # type: ignore

DRVI Model Training

A DRVI model with 16 latent dimensions is trained to capture cell type-level variation. The model regresses out capture batch effects (donor timepoint combinations) while preserving biological cell type structure.

In[]:
# Normalize, log-transform, and select 2000 HVGs per batch
batch = 'capture_batch'

adata.layers['counts'] = adata.X.copy() # type: ignore

scanpy.pp.normalize_total(adata, target_sum=1e4)
scanpy.pp.log1p(adata)

adata.raw = adata.copy() # type: ignore

scanpy.pp.highly_variable_genes(
    adata, flavor='seurat_v3', span=1, subset=True,
    batch_key=batch, layer='counts', n_top_genes=2000
)
In[]:
# Train DRVI model (16 latents, regressing out capture_batch)
batch_key = ['capture_batch']

drvi.model.DRVI.setup_anndata(adata, layer='counts', categorical_covariate_keys=batch_key, is_count_data=True)

model = drvi.model.DRVI(adata, n_latent=16, categorical_covariates=batch_key)

model.train(max_epochs=40, early_stopping=True)

Dimensionality Reduction and Clustering

UMAP is computed on the DRVI latent space for visualization, and Leiden clustering is applied to identify distinct cell type populations.

scanpy.tl.leiden(adata, resolution=0.2)

Cluster Characterization and Validation

Clusters are characterized by computing correlations between latent dimensions and cluster assignments. Canonical cell type markers are used to validate cluster identities, and cluster composition is examined across donors and timepoints.

In[]:
# Randomize cell order for visualization
scanpy.pp.subsample(adata, fraction=1.0)
In[]:
# Visualize UMAP colored by cluster, time, and donor
scanpy.settings.set_figure_params(figsize=(6, 5)) # type: ignore
scanpy.pl.umap(adata, color=['leiden', 'time_point', 'donor'], size=8, alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black', linewidth=0.1, frameon=False)
In[]:
# Compute and plot latent-cluster correlation heatmap
# Compute correlation matrix: clusters  latents
obsm_key = 'X_drvi'
cluster_key = 'leiden'

Z = numpy.asarray(adata.obsm[obsm_key])
clusters = adata.obs[cluster_key].astype(str).values
clus_names = sorted(numpy.unique(clusters)) # type: ignore

# Correlation per cluster  latent
corr_matrix = []
for c in clus_names:
    y = (clusters == c).astype(float)
    r = [numpy.corrcoef(Z[:, j], y)[0, 1] for j in range(Z.shape[1])]
    corr_matrix.append(r)

corr_df = pandas.DataFrame(corr_matrix,
                           index=clus_names,
                           columns=[f'DR {i+1}' for i in range(Z.shape[1])])

# Heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(corr_df, cmap='RdBu_r', center=0, vmin=-0.5, vmax=0.5,
            cbar_kws={'label': 'Correlation'}, linewidths=0)

plt.title('Latent-Cluster Associations')
plt.xlabel('DRVI Latent Dimension')
plt.ylabel('Leiden Cluster')
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Show top 2 latents per cluster
print("\nTop 2 latents per cluster:")
for c in clus_names:
    top_latents = corr_df.loc[c].abs().nlargest(2) # type:ignore
    print(f"Cluster {c}: {', '.join([f'{lat} (r={corr_df.loc[c, lat]:.2f})' for lat in top_latents.index])}")

Differential Expression Analysis

Wilcoxon rank-sum tests are performed to identify genes that are specifically upregulated in each cluster compared to all other cells.

In[]:
# Perform differential expression analysis per cluster
adata.var['symbol'] = ~adata.var_names.str.contains('ENSG', na=False)

scanpy.tl.rank_genes_groups(adata, groupby='leiden', method='wilcoxon', use_raw=False, mask_var='symbol')

deg_up = scanpy.get.rank_genes_groups_df(adata, group=None, pval_cutoff=0.01, log2fc_min=0)
# deg_up = markers.query('pvals_adj < 0.01 and logfoldchanges > 0').copy()
In[]:
# Extract top 5 upregulated genes per cluster
top_up_genes = (deg_up
        .sort_values(['group', 'logfoldchanges'], ascending=[True, False])
        .groupby('group')
        .head(5)
        .reset_index(drop=True))
